pull_request.title: Add PMU+PERF benchmarking code
pull_request.body:
This PR adds benchmarking code using either the PMU cycle counter or perf. 
For using PMU, user-space access to PMU registers is required (need to be enabled through a corresponding kernel module).
for using perf, the kernel needs to have `perf` support.
It's based on https://github.com/slothy-optimizer/pqax

We'll have a separate PR for MacOS benchmarks to fully address #28. 

This also adds a `tests bench` command that runs the benchmarks for all parameter sets.
You can either run  `tests bench --cycles PMU` or `tests bench --cycles PERF`. It defaults to `tests bench --cycles NO` which will always print zeros. 

In parallel, @potsrevennil and I are setting up CI to run those benchmarks on a RPi4 (Arm Cortex-A72). We'll add that in a separate PR. 

The current nwarmup/niteration/ntest work reasonably well on the A72. For other cores, we'll have to adjust. Once everything work as we want it in CI, maybe we want to go for a few more iterations to get more stable benchmarks.

This PR depends on #68

I Added a benchmark workflow. Note that the workflow will only run on `main` branch or PR labeled as `benchmark`. The `tests` script is also refactored a bit in order to show the benchmark summary on GitHub action.

I refactored the `nix` shell specification in order to speed up ci, and also
disabled ci jobs running on self-host runner when pushed to fork repositories by the way.
